text="Which bijection?">Which <fr:link
href="jms-00KR.xml"
title="Bijection"
addr="jms-00KR"
type="local">bijection</fr:link>?</fr:title><fr:taxon>Remark</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Although we are speaking of “being isomorphic” as the property of there being a <fr:link
href="jms-00KR.xml"
title="Bijection"
addr="jms-00KR"
type="local">bijection</fr:link> between them, in practice, it is almost <fr:em>never</fr:em> useful to know that there exists some undetermined <fr:link
href="jms-00KR.xml"
title="Bijection"
addr="jms-00KR"
type="local">bijection</fr:link> between given sets; it is always important to know <fr:em>which</fr:em> <fr:link
href="jms-00KR.xml"
title="Bijection"
addr="jms-00KR"
type="local">bijection</fr:link>. Indeed, we have seen in <fr:link
href="jms-00KT.xml"
title="Counting bijections between finite sets"
addr="jms-00KT"
type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number
addr="jms-00KT" /></fr:link> that there can be many distinct <fr:link
href="jms-00KR.xml"
title="Bijection"
addr="jms-00KR"
type="local">bijections</fr:link> between two sets.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
