type="user">jms-00IN</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00IN.xml</fr:route><fr:title
text="Relational composite">Relational composite</fr:title><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Given <fr:link
href="jms-00I7.xml"
title="Relation"
addr="jms-00I7"
type="local">relations</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R\colon  A\mathbin {\nrightarrow } B]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S\colon  B\mathbin {\nrightarrow } C]]></fr:tex>, we can define the <fr:em><fr:strong>relational composite</fr:strong></fr:em> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S\circ  R\colon  A\mathbin {\nrightarrow } C]]></fr:tex> in a way that generalises composition of functions. In particular, we define <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S\circ  R]]></fr:tex> to be the following subset of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A\times  C]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p><fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[
 \begin {aligned}
 S\circ  R &\colon  A\mathbin {\nrightarrow } C\\
  S\circ  R &=
  {\mathopen {}\left \{
   {\mathopen {}\left (a,c\right )\mathclose {}}\in  A\times  C
   \mid 
   \exists  b\in  B\mathpunct {.}
   a\mathrel {R}b \land  b\mathrel {S} c
  \right \}\mathclose {}}
 \end {aligned}
]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
